\begin{abstract}
The Global Change Assessment Model, an integrated assessment model, provides insight into the the interactions and feedbacks between physical and human systems. It is used extensively to simulate the response of terrestrial systems to exogenous factors such as population growth, technological improvements and economic and environmental policies. Output from the land system component of GCAM, which simulates land use activities and the production of major crops, is at the subregional level and must be spatially downscaled in order to use with gridded impact assessment models. However, existing downscaling routines typically consider cropland as a homogeneous class and do not provide information about land use intensity or specific management practices such as irrigation and multiple cropping. This paper presents a spatial allocation model to downscale crop production data from GCAM to a spatial grid, producing a time series of maps showing the spatial distribution of specific crops (e.g. rice, wheat, maize) at four input levels (subsistence, low input rainfed, high input rainfed and high input irrigated). The model algorithm is constrained by available cropland at each time point and therefore implicitly balances extensification and intensification processes in order to meet global food demand. It utilises a stochastic approach such that an increase in production of a particular crop is more likely to occur in grid cells with a high biophysical suitability and neighbourhood influence, whereas a fall in regional production will translate to reduced area in cells with lower suitability. User-supplied rules define the order in which specific crops are downscaled as well as allowable transitions. The ability of the model to reproduce historical trends in India is evaluated by comparing the model output with an historical spatio-temporal dataset showing the change in spatial distribution of rainfed and irrigated crops between 1970--2010. Lastly, a regional case study demonstrates the ability of the model to predict the spatial distribution of crops in India under different GCAM scenarios. 
\end{abstract}


