\introduction  %% \introduction[modified heading if necessary]

Population growth, demographic changes and economic development are expected to cause a dramatic increase in global food demand over the coming decades \citep{}. At the same time, the area of land available for food production will be constrained by human activities such as urbanization, infrastructure development and bioenergy production, and depleted resources in previously productive regions as a result of unsustainable agricultural practices \citep{lotze-campen_global_2008}. Consequently, agricultural intensification, whereby production is increased without increasing the area of land devoted to agriculture, will play an increasingly important roles in achieving global food security \citep{}. However, the various management practices required to increase crop yield, such as irrigation, fertilizer and mechanization, are associated with environmental degradation which reduces the sustainability and resilience of the food supply system \citep[e.g.][]{}. Thus, detailed modelling of the environmental impact of future agricultural expansion and intensification is essential in order to assess the sustainability of global food security \citep{}. Since the rate of degradation is highly dependent upon local conditions and agricultural practices, there is a need to produce spatially explicit predictions about the rate and location of change. \\

% In many cases GCAM may be used successfully as a standalone model \citep[e.g.][]{}. Alternatively, it may be coupled with domain-specific models to assess the impacts of change on particular sectors.
The Global Change Assessment Model (GCAM) \citep{}, an integrated assessment model (IAM), has been developed to gain insight into coupled human-natural systems and simulate their future co-evolution with explicit representation of the various feedbacks that exist between them \citep{le_page_downscaling_2016}. The model is divided into coupled subsystems representing the global economy, energy systems, agriculture and land use. It is used extensively to simulate the response of terrestrial systems to exogenous factors such as population growth, technological improvements and economic and environmental policies \citep[e.g.][]{}. A key feature of GCAM is its detailed representation of the agricultural sector and its relationship with other sectors in the global economy \citep{}. Output from the land system component of GCAM, which simulates land use activities and the production of major crops, is at the subregional level and must be spatially downscaled in order to use with gridded impact assessment models \citep{lotze-campen_global_2008}. Coupling these two classes of models is recognised as an important technical challenge \citep{nazemi_inclusion_2015}. However, existing downscaling routines typically consider cropland as a homogeneous class and do not provide information about land use intensity or specific management practices such as irrigation and multiple cropping \citep{}. \\

A recent addition to GCAM is a land use model, GCAMLU \citep{le_page_downscaling_2016}, which downscales regional predictions of land use and land cover change to a 0.5 $\times$ 0.5 degree spatial grid. The algorithm follows an ordered approach in which land use and land cover types, as well as certain crops, are spatially downscaled in order of decreasing economic value \citep{}. A feature of the model is the inclusion of a user-defined target level of intensification versus expansion of agricultural land. The model attempts to meet the specified demand while also satisfying the requirements of non-agricultural land use types. Additional parameters define transition priorities and spatial constaints. The algorithm is based on the assumption that land use and land cover expansion tends to occur in areas where the land use is already present \citep[e.g.][]{}. This effect is represented by calculating the ``kernel density'' for each land use type, which quantitatively describes the proximity and density of a given land use around a grid cell. The suitability of grid cells to agricultural land is additionally based on nutrient availability and soil workability according to the Harmonised World Soil Database \citep{}. While GCAMLU is an appropriate solution for various types of environmental change studies, it lacks the appropriate level of detail for assessing environmental impacts of agricultural intensification, particularly those associated with the consumption of resources \citep{}. For example, the model does not explicitly represent crop rotations, nor does it include important management practices such as irrigation, fertilizer application and multiple cropping. \\

There have been some previous attempts to address the problem. For example, \citet{hurtt_harmonization_2011} developed a simple downscaling procedure for the IPCC 5th Assessment Report in which grid level estimates of crop area from \citep{ref} were scaled with national level estimates of change. Several impact assessment models contain inbuilt downscaling routines. However, while such methods may be suitable for hindcasting experiments in which the intensification process is reversed, they are less well suited to future simulations because they fail to account for the spatial and temporal heterogeneity of biophysical and socioeconomic constraints on future crop production. The Model of Agricultural Production and its Impact on the Environment (MAgPIE) \citep{lotze-campen_global_2008} is a global land use optimisation model which consists of a regional demand model coupled with a gridded supply model (the LPJmL model \citep{}). An inbuilt land use model determines the spatial allocation of various agricultural production activities by minimizing the total cost of production of a given regional demand \citep{lotze-campen_global_2008}. The production cost, which is defined in terms of cost per unit food energy, varies spatially as a result of differences in potential yield between grid cells \citep{lotze-campen_impacts_2014}. (TODO: find a more detailed explanation of this process - limitations may include the failure to consider sub-optimal production systems which arise for cultural reasons). \\

In this paper we develop a computationally efficient algorithm to spatially downscale crop production scenarios from GCAM. The main output of the downscaling algorithm is a time series of maps showing the spatial distribution of specific crops (e.g. rice, wheat, maize) at four input levels (subsistence, low input rainfed, high input rainfed and high input irrigated). The remainder of this paper is divided into four sections. First, we provide a brief overview of the GCAM model with particular emphasis on its representation of the agricultural sector and its links and feedbacks with other system components. We then describe the downscaling algorithm and its data requirements, as well as describing the pre-processing to transform the raw input data prior to a simulation. We demonstrate the model through an example application to India; a region which provides a useful testbed for the concept and implementation of the model because of its complex agricultural systems and projected population and socioeconomic change. Lastly, we discuss the limitations of the model, highlight potential use cases and identify areas for improvement. \\

