The principal model input is regional crop production values from the GCAM simulation. Initial crop area maps are provided by the MapSPAM product \citet{you_generating_2014}; a dataset which shows the spatial distribution, as well as the corresponding yield and production values, of 42 crops around the year 2005 at a spatial resolution of 5 $\times$ 5 arcminutes. A unique feature of the MapSPAM product compared to other similar datasets (e.g. MIRCA2000 \citet{portmann_mirca2000-global_2010}) is that it differentiates between irrigated and rainfed cropland and high, intermediate and subsistence input levels \citep{you_generating_2014}. GCAM explicitly models 3 single crop classes (Rice, Wheat, Maize) and 8 aggregated crop classes, each containing several subcrops. We use the MapSPAM production data to disaggregate these crop classes, initially assuming that the proportion of subcrops within the main crop class remains the same during the simulation period. This assumption is relaxed during runtime if the specified production cannot be met, allowing for the fact that at any point during the simulation certain subcrops within a GCAM region may be approaching their maximum production while others may have greater potential for upscaling. Crop calendars from AQUASTAT (irrigated crops only) and MIRCA2000 (irrigated and rainfed crops) are used to temporally disaggregate crop production maps into growing seasons. This is necessary to account for multiple cropping in regions where more than one growing season is possible during a calendar year. \\

