\subsection{Downscaling algorithm}
The downscaling algorithm is based on the assumption that an increase in the production of a particular crop is more likely to happen in grid cells with a high suitability and neighbourhood influence, whereas a fall in production will tend to occur in grid cells with relatively low suitability values and/or a low neighbourhood influence. We assume that crop production can be increased either by expanding the area of land devoted to growing the crop or by intensifying agricultural production in order to increase crop yield \citep{lotze-campen_impacts_2014}. The former can be achieved by converting existing cropland previously allocated to another crop or by converting non-agricultural land to cropland, while the latter is achieved by increasing the use of the main inputs (e.g. water, fertilizer, labour, technology) that enable crop growth. These physical processes are expressed in the downscaling algorithm as three separate routines. The first of these routines simulates the \textit{conversion} of land with decreasing regional production to crops with increasing production. The second routine simulates the \textit{intensification} of existing agricultural land, and the last routine simulates the \textit{expansion} of land to unallocated cropland. \\

The algorithm downscales each crop type in turn following a user-supplied hierarchy which is supposed to reflect the perceived relative economic value of the various crops. This approach, which is used in various spatially explicit land use change models \citep[e.g.][]{fuchs_high-resolution_2013,moulds_open_2015,le_page_downscaling_2016}, results in a stable and computationally efficient algorithm because it removes the need to dynamically simulate competition between crop types, which usually entails an iterative procedure \citep[e.g.][]{verburg_combining_2009}. The user is required to supply the order of the 11 GCAM crop types, rather than the 42 crops represented in the MapSPAM dataset, with the allocation order of subcrops within the aggregate GCAM classes determined endogeneously. A rotational constraint parameter is introduced to define the maximum allowable fraction of available cropland in a grid cell \citep{lotze-campen_global_2008}, which effectively forces a user-supplied proportion of cropland to be left fallow. \\

