At the beginning of the allocation procedure the area belonging to crops with decreasing regional production is converted to a holding class which retains the input level of the previous time point but discards the crop type (e.g. high-input irrigated wheat $\rightarrow$ unallocated high-input irrigated cropland). We assume that a fall in production is predominantly achieved by converting cropland to another crop category rather than through de-intensification. Conversion of crops to the holding category takes place in an ordered way such that each crop type is considered in turn, although the order itself does not influence the result. For a given crop type, each pixel/input-level combination is considered as a separate entity with a unique suitability value (i.e. pixel A, rainfed wheat is considered as separate from pixel A, irrigated wheat). Starting with the pixel/input-level combination with the lowest suitability, a small amount of land is subtracted from the area of the crop in the pixel. The quantity removed is multiplied by the corresponding yield value of pixel \textit{i}, input-level \textit{j} and subtracted from the regional total. The algorithm proceeds through pixel/input-level combinations in order of increasing suitability until the regional production target is met. If the regional demand is not met after considering each eligible pixel/input-level combination the procedure is repeated. \\

Having dealt with crop types with falling regional production, the algorithm moves on to consider crops with increasing regional production. A first round of intensification is initiated in which the algorithm attempts to achieve a user supplied target. This could specify, for instance, that 25\% of the increase in wheat production should come from intensification. Crops are considered in the user-supplied order which represents the perceived economic value of the crops at the regional level. Pixels are arranged according to the suitability of the highest input level present in the pixel. The intensification module shifts a small amount of land from a lower input level to a higher input level, and the change in production is calculated and subtracted from the regional target. This process continues until the target intensification is met, or no more intensification is possible. \\

The next part of the allocation routine attempts to allocate the outstanding crop production through the process of extensification. As in the opposite case, when crops with falling demand are considered, each pixel/input-level combination is treated separately and arranged in order from high suitability to low suitability, discounting pixels which do not contain unallocated cropland. In each case, a small area of unallocated cropland is assigned to the crop currently under consideration. This process continues until either the production target is met or no more suitable unallocated cropland exists. \\

Lastly, a second round of intensification is applied to crops which have not met their regional production target (for this reason there may be more intensification than the target). As in the first round of intensification, pixels are selected until the regional production target is met. In cases where this is still not possible we assume that the region cannot achieve the target production. Optionally, the user may select to distribute the outstanding production between the other subcrops within the main GCAM crop type. If this has been done for any subcrop the algorithm returns to the top of the allocation routine (the first round of intensification) and repeats the allocation process. \\

