\section{Discussion}

\noindent Discussion points:

\begin{itemize}
  \item Uncertainty arising from assumption of static biophysical constraints, and potential to couple with Earth system models
  \item Future changes in crop yield
  \item Data requirements
  \item Uncertainty quantification
  \item Importance of simplicity to enable running the model multiple times
  \item Other points arising from model evaluation/example application
\end{itemize}  

The MapSPAM potential yield product, which informs our estimation of crop suitability and is key to the allocation process, only considers contemporary biophysical constraints. Over time, factors such as soil erosion, salinisation, waterlogging and groundwater depletion, which often arise due to unsustainable agricultural intensification, may decrease the potential crop yield in many areas and simultaneously reduce the likelihood of crop expansion as well as reducing the yield of crops currently grown in those areas. Meanwhile social constraints on production such as access to labour may also change over time, particularly in regions where there is rapid socioeconomic change. At present none of these dynamic constaints are explicitly considered in the downscaling framework, although the inclusion of dynamic population density maps may implicitly address some of the socioeconomic factors. Including the dynamic biophysical constraints in the downscaling framework will require the addition of an Earth system model which is capable of representing the various physical processes, as well as including the required meteorological data required to force these models. \\

% The FAO GAEZ methodology in theory provides... However, data access to this resource is challenging. In our view, improving the interface to spatial input data would improve the ability of researchers... Moreover, opening the source code used for generating the datasest would be a... which would improve the ability of researchers to update the dataset according to their specific needs.

Climate change and socioeconomic development will affect crop yield \citep{iizumi_responses_2017}. A simplistic approach is used to account for the former, while crop yield increases as a result of socioeconomic change is not currently considered. \\

The model requires a large amount of data in order to provide meaningful results. As the case study demonstrates, a degree of familiarity with agriculture in the region under consideration is necessary. The required input data is based on publicly-available, global datasets. \\

The model follows an ordered approach which is computationally efficient but fails to represent competition between crop classes. Thus, an important input to the model is the order in which crops are allocated (TODO: assess the sensitivity of the model to changing the allocation order). Uncertainty may be accounted for by stochastically changing the order of crop allocation over several runs in order to build up a probability distribution describing the spatial distribution of various crops. These can either be combined in some way or used in subsequent analyses as a probabilistic input. \\

Separate treatment of land use constraints in GCAM and the downscaling algorithm may give rise to inconsistencies. Integrated models such as MAgPIE include representations of both the macroeconomy and land use. Coupling GCAM with a spatially-explicit land use change model would allow for more detailed consideration of the various constaints on agricultural production and the feedbacks to other parts of the macroeconomy system. Eventually, the downscaling algorithm presented here should be dynamically coupled with GCAM or another IAM to properly assess the feedback between land use change and other parts of the human-natural system. The most recent version of GCAM contains a formal mechanism with which establish a two-way coupling with other models. \\

An important design feature of the algorithm is to ensure the algorithm is computationally efficient and \textit{fast}, enabling rapid generation of multiple scenarios of agricultural land use change. This design paradigm aligns with that of integrated assessment models, which are usually run multiple times [thousands - provide reference?] with varying initialisations and parameter values in order to capture uncertainty. Future developments should adhere to this philosophy to ensure its continued applicability to global change research. \\

